 step by step solution
step 1:

It's obvious that the answer is "NO" if $a_{i} = 0$ for all $1 \le i \le n$.

step 2:

Lets prove that the answer is "YES" if $a_{i} = 1$ for at least one $1 \le i \le n$.

step 3:

If size of $a$ is equal to $k$, just use second type operation once and we are done.

step 4:

Otherwise (if $|a| \gt k$), there will be three cases: (assume that $a_{j} = 1$)

• if $j \gt 2$, you can use first type operation on first and second element and decrease size of $a$ by 1.   
• else if $j \lt |a|-1$, you can use first type operation on last and second to last element and decrease size of $a$ by 1.   
• else, it can be shown easily that $|a| = 3$ and $k = 2$ so you can use second type operation twice and turn $a$ into a single $1$. 
In first and second case, you can continue decreasing size of $a$ until $|a| = k$ (or you reach $3$-rd case) and you can use second type operation to reach your aim.

step 5:

So we proved that the answer is "YES" iff $a_{i} = 1$ for at least one $1 \le i \le n$ or in other words, iff $\sum_{i = 1}^n a_{i} \gt 0$.
 solution
```
// In the name of God
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while(t--)
    {
        int n, k;
        cin >> n >> k;
        int sum = 0;
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++){
            int a;
            cin >> a;
            sum += a;
        }
        if(sum > 0) cout << "YES" << endl;
        else cout << "NO" << endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
// Thank God

